    <h1>RevEmo</h1>
    <p class="subtitle">Revenue per Emotional Moment</p>
    <p class="meta">
      Version 1.0 · Published 19 May 2026 · Last updated 19 May 2026 · Status: working paper, under review at <em>International Journal of Hospitality Management</em> · Canonical URL: optimisationblindness.org/revemo
    </p>

    <h2>In plain terms</h2>

    <p>RevEmo measures whether emotionally meaningful service moments create measurable economic value for a hotel.</p>

    <p>RevEmo is the property-level application of <a href="/concept">optimisation blindness</a>. <a href="/deqi">DEQI</a> is the destination-level application. The two are not separate ideas. They are two applications of the same concern: that optimisation systems can create measurable value while eroding forms of value they were not designed to measure.</p>

    <h2>Why hotels need it</h2>

    <p>Hotels already measure occupancy, ADR, RevPAR, NPS, reviews, and guest satisfaction. What they usually do not measure is the economic value of the specific human moments that make a guest spend more, return, extend, refer, or remember the property differently. RevEmo was developed to make those moments measurable.</p>

    <p>RevEmo does not argue that emotion is soft or immeasurable. It argues that some emotional moments have observable commercial consequences, and that a higher-resolution instrument is needed to see them.</p>

    <h2>What counts as an emotional moment</h2>

    <p>RevEmo treats emotional moments as operational events. A moment matters when it can be located in the guest journey and associated with observable commercial effects: upgrade acceptance, ancillary spend, stay extension, repeat visitation, referral, lifetime value, or asset valuation over time.</p>

    <p>Moments are identifiable, locatable in time and space within the property, and bounded by observable changes in guest behaviour. The questions RevEmo addresses are operational. Which moments produce the largest economic uplift? Which produce no uplift despite consuming operational resources? Which produce negative effects that conventional service-quality instruments fail to detect? Which staff interactions, design choices, or service flows reliably produce moments worth investing in?</p>

    <h2>What RevEmo measures</h2>

    <p>RevEmo operates at the scale of the property and the individual guest encounter. It quantifies the impact of specific emotional moments on three downstream economic outcomes: revenue uplift during the current stay, retention through repeat visitation and lifetime value, and the asset valuation of the property over time.</p>

    <p>Conventional service-quality measurement aggregates across the stay. It produces satisfaction scores, NPS values, and review averages. These are useful but coarse. They cannot identify the specific moments in which value is created or lost, and they cannot answer the question of which operational investments will produce the largest emotional and economic return.</p>

    <h2>Scale and unit of analysis</h2>

    <p>The unit of analysis is the guest encounter within a single property over the duration of a stay. The framework can be aggregated across stays for retention and asset-valuation analysis, but the underlying measurement is encounter-level. This distinguishes RevEmo from DEQI, which operates at the destination level and measures aggregate effects across multiple properties, platforms, and infrastructures within a tourism city.</p>

    <p>RevEmo is what an operator uses to manage a property. DEQI is what a destination authority uses to manage a city.</p>

    <h2>Relationship to optimisation blindness</h2>

    <p>RevEmo is the property-level operationalisation of the broader <a href="/concept">optimisation blindness</a> concept. Most hospitality optimisation systems — revenue management, channel management, operational dashboards, guest-relationship platforms — optimise for measurable signals that occur after a guest has already decided to engage. RevEmo identifies the emotional moments that produce or destroy the decision to engage in the first place, and that determine whether a guest returns. These moments are systematically invisible to conventional optimisation. RevEmo makes them visible.</p>

    <h2>Status</h2>

    <p>RevEmo is currently in academic review at the <em>International Journal of Hospitality Management</em>. The full mathematical specification, measurement protocols, and empirical validation strategy will be available with the published paper. A working paper version will be posted to a preprint server upon journal acceptance.</p>

